The mother's school is also part of offices that included architects.
the Avriopoint administrative building of Brno is the new headquarters of Arch. Design.
No one could have expected it to also house a mini kindergarten with all it takes - walls of colors, imaginative furniture, toys and finally a miniature playground on the terrace.
Since October last year, children of Arch. design employees can go there.
The Arch. Design architectural project company, whose workshops have produced a large number of constructions in Brno, has imagined its mini-home business school since the first drafts of the Avriopoint building.
It employs about 90 people, especially children's age, and it was important for women architects and project managers to be able to get back to work quickly.
At the same time as shorter employment contracts, the kindergarten is a bonus offered to its employees by Arch. Design. as part of its social program.
Manufacturers and architects thus have the opportunity to combine work with care for children.
It was the employees of Arch.Design themselves who imagined this kindergarten and with the support of management they were able to obtain an endowment from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The mini-maternal school is funded through the European Social Fund through the operational programme of human resources and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
With funding facilities (with 2.8 thousand Czech crowns), they were able to purchase equipment and equipment and after two years to ensure qualified staff and start-up.
After the use of the funding allocation (two years) the company Arch. Design. has an obligation after 3 years to operate the mini kindergarten on its own funds.
The preparation of the project lasted a year and it was the Economy rating company that helped make the application for staffing.
Care for children is provided by qualified staff, a nurse and a nurse throughout the day take care of children. Children can go to kindergarten without age restrictions, but they have more than three years for most.
As this is a "minimum mother's school" there can only be 5 children present at the same time, but during the day there are more children who replace each other.
The functioning of the school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use this school without looking at the hierarchical position.
Although it is individual care and education, the mini-maternal school program is comparable to that for pre-school education.
It is not only for children to play, but also for quality education - from beginning to preparation for school benches English is taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys and imaginative games but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children in society creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can at any time control their children and do not have the stress of delay to go to a school away from the parent's workplace.
Parents use their working time in the most productive way.
It is not surprising that there is a natural relationship of loyalty between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design.s's is thus listed among companies that offer a bonus of choice for the recruitment of new employees and are friendly to the family and through this program reinforces HR marketing.
The bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look inside Gaudi.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric sarien, the staircase to a spine of dinosaur and balconies to open fish mouths.
This is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona by architect Antoni Gaudi.
Because of its organic forms, the house received from the premises the nickname House in bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaic, facade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present of curves, here is all that is typical for the Art New of Antoni Gaudi.
The front fa√ßade of the house runs its dream lines, its pleasing colors and textures that remind the nature and the animals.
In a more detailed observation, we see geometry, rhythm and order thought with precision.
In the night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit so that the impression of brightness of the colors is strengthened.
The winding and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood vaguely copies the window frames, the balustrades, the decorative elements of the doors, the oeilleton and the blades.
The Battlo house that stands in the Eixample neighborhood in Passeig de Gracia street in number. 43, was born from the construction of a house of 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, first stressed the demolition of the old construction and the construction of another completely new but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of unusual and better market reconstruction.
But Casa Battlo's idea as a multiple-bedroom house was not thought by Gaudi alone.
Architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely on his project that the decorations for an apartment representing the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade were born.
Other artists and creators also worked for the facade.
The joint work for the plans of Casa Battlo began with successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of the house of Gaudi Casa Mila and Guell Park in which there are other works of Gaudi.
The premises nicknamed the house hot just after its completion because of its organic forms "the House in Bones".
Others, in view of the specific mechanism of opening the windows have called it "the house that dances".
It is said that at the top of the construction there is a sword similar to that of Saint George the patron of Catalonia.
Other elements of sculpture of construction contain hidden religious motives.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with air events and typical fireplaces.
Their 45-degree inclination seems strange.
During the creation of Gaudi absolutely failed to comply with the then construction directives and did not allow themselves to be hindered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained from the city the permit to build, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years after the completion the municipal council was horrified and asked for modifications.
He did not like, for example, the members of the municipal council that the pillars of the construction impinge on the public pavement.
There was never a change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the call of the city Josep Battlo asked (and got satisfaction) for permission to rent the two top floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and in the third there was a room and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented at a jewelry store.
The entire house of six floors is shared by a staircase by which you reach up to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of reconstruction and replaced by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of binding spaces.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the salons and the high society can communicate comfortably or be limited to private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi has also received new facades a non-traditional roof and two additional floors.
Gaudi's game with light is also impressive, blue and white glass tiles with which the inner courtyard is decorated and with light wells.
The two-coloured game gives maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply enough to bet on the principle that the white reflects more than the dark that instead absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house, which was registered in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund, may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and beautiful apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued their visits because they found it to be a lucrative business and expanded the scope of visits to common spaces and to the barn, including roof terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really cheap and costs 16.50 euros; students, retirees, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the entry price in the other constructions of Gaudi in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic towers, you must quickly find a friend among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
