The European Union changes the rules for obtaining visas
People must go to Visa Applicants' Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; waiting time will be reduced.
From 10 January 2011, the procedure for the treatment of visas at the Embassy and consulates of the United States will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will be required to attend the Visa Applicant Service Centres (ASC) prior to their interview with the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be revised by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will provide certain benefits for applicants, including the following:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to obtain an appointment, another payment for the processing of the visa and another for the courier service to deliver the document.
The aspirant will make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
Those who wish to renew their visas will not be required to attend an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only present themselves at the nearest AUC where they will present the documents and be fingerprinted.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be collected in the CSA, applicants who want a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain there less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Ju√°rez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boltines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
