Revenge hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as a scandal only in the case of hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound international changes, and prefigures a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that each file consisting of a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press cuts.
The "extraordinary" American revelations on the sexual habits of Berlusconi only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those whose Berlusconi owns), and Khadafi's caricature sinister profile has long been for artists of cabaret subject to sketch.
The rule that secret records should be composed of only new ones already known is essential to the dynamics of secret services, not just in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Ch√¢teau, Templiers or Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in the earlier works.
And not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (he doesn't know where to look for news about the nonexistent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe only that they already know, and who reconfirms what they have already learned.
That's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same for secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited in spirit) the head of secret services (unless he may be, I know, editor at Lib√©ration), who only retain what he recognizes as true.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy of Rome sent to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every cultivated person already knows, that the embassies, at least since the end of World War II, and since the heads of states can call or take an airplane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises of representation, have become spy centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows that very well, and it is only by hypocrisy that they pretend to ignore it.
However, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to place American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that a hacker could capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the state department.
So the scandal doesn't make both victims and "bourreaux" into crisis.
But let's come to the deep nature of what happened.
So, at Orwell's time, we could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely proven since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction carried out, the hotel visited, the road borrowed and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the power eye.
But when it is demonstrated, as it happens now, that even the crypts of power secrets cannot escape a hacker's control, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
The power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected revenger of the citizen - can know all the secrets of the power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said it, that a real secret is an empty secret (and empty secret can never be revealed); it is true, too, that everything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, because it belongs to the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means to remove all power from him.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but did too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is clear that in the future, States will no longer be able to put online any reserved information - it would be necessary to publish it on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it is just as obvious that with current technologies, it is futile to hope that confidential telephone relations can be maintained.
Nothing easier than to find out if and when a head of state moved on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relations be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the moment, my prediction falls within the scope of science fiction and is therefore Romanesque, but I am obliged to imagine government officials who discreetly move in due diligence to uncontrollable routes, being only bearers of messages learned by heart or, at the most, hiding the little information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept as a single copy in key drawers: in the background, the Watergate espionage attempt has been less successful than WikiLeaks.
I've had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving in crabs, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegrapher revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a wire telegraph (telephones).
Video cassettes (analogic) allowed film researchers to explore a movie step by step, going forward and backward and discovering all the secrets of assembly, while now CDs (digitals) only allow them to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while flying, and the travel it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that the communication policy and techniques are back to horse cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was going on in the secret of the embassies.
It is now the embassies who request confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France bidouille its promises of financing
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine the implementation of the promises of rapidly unblocked funding (such fast start or early funding) made by developed countries.
And the big French biduillages are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged EUR 7.2 billion over three years and France EUR 1.26 billion (or 420 million per year).
At the opening of the COP16, the EU came out the big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, large side event, distribution of brochures...
