The EU announces that it has released ‚Ç¨2.2 billion in 2010, which sets it on the right track to meet its commitment of ‚Ç¨7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must, according to the Copenhagen agreement, be "new and additional", in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being to the detriment of official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States whose France blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the best reference.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years for fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the other hand, France believes that funding for "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure in previous years or at the overall level of official development assistance.
Specifically, the total amount of France's support for developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funding...
Another crucial element is the division between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses his or her method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that 1‚Ç¨ loan equivalent to 1‚Ç¨ given.
Of course, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for some investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions based on more efficient technologies), it is necessary to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At the most, should be counted under its commitments only the cost of the loan for the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has no such reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million by making 91.5% of loans (EUR 380.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (EUR 36.1 million) - see the EU document to verify for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in other cases) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts 1‚Ç¨ to meet its commitment, France only puts 10 cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
Nice pass-by tour!
In short, in its fast start financing, France operates a double swindling: on the one hand, on the evolution of action over time and on the reality of financial effort.
By spending only EUR 36.1 million, she can make it believe that she spends 420 million "new and additional" in line with her promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has done the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely duped...
The chapter on early funding is only a small, relatively short-term issue compared to all climate discussions.
But it could be an extra sand grain in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that will not be the case.
In any event, it is essential to learn early funding from this first year.
First, France could announce a change in its way of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of compliance with its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could move forward discussions on long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently discussed): one will not escape the question of "additionality" or the way in which loans are recorded.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore based on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would be of a kind to increase the level of international confidence needed to advance the discussions.
Child-ingested pesticides warning
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemical substances on a day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Generations Futures Association (former Movement for Rights and Respect for Future Generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no significant statistical value in relation to the low number of samples analysed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", bought food usually consumed in four meals and one incas in one day by a child of about ten years in the Oise and Paris supermarkets between July and September.
These typical meals, including official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day - as well as snacks, were examined by laboratories seeking chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The assessment of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are classified as potential or probable carcinogens and five carcinogenic substances, some as well as 37 substances that may act as endocrine disruptors (PE), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Even if, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, we see in our investigation that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is worrying," the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three proven as certain carcinogens as well as about twenty residues that could disturb the hormone system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as incas from the study, presents traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenya's green beans, included in lunch, on which the study detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, the steak, tuna box, and even the bread bag and chewing gum were full of pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroforms.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the richest with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to heat the microwave meal was not exempt.
The final risk to the consumer of this "contaminant cocktails" "is probably underestimated", according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, proposed "face to the urgency of the situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "increasing civilization diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
